Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP):

*Most internet communications are made with web requests through the HTTP protocol. HTTP is an application-level protocol used to access the World Wide Web resources. The term "hypertext" stands for text containing links to other resources and text that the readers can easily interpret. HTTP consists of a client server where the client requests the server for a resource. The server processes the request and returns the requested resource. The default port for HTTP communications is PORT 80, though this can be changed to any port depending on the web server configuration. The same requests are utilized when we use the internet to visit different websites. We enter a Fully Qualified Domain Name (DQDN) as a Uniform Resource Locator (URL) to reach the desired websites like "www.hackthebox.com".
-------------------------------------

URL:

Resources over HTTP are accessed via URL which offers many more specifications than simplifying a website we want to visit. 
-----------------------------------

URL Structure:
http://admin:password@inlanefreight.com:80/dashboard.php?login=true#status

"http" is the scheme, "inlanefreight.com" is the host, "dashboard.php" is the path, and "status" is the fragment.

Here is what each component stands for:

Component	Example			Description
Scheme		ttp:// https://		This is used to identify the protocol being accessed by the client, and ends with a colon and a double slash (://)
User Info	admin:password@		This is an optional component that contains the credentials (separated by a colon :) used to authenticate to the host, and is separated from the host with an at sign (@)
Host		inlanefreight.com	The host signifies the resource location. This can be a hostname or an IP address
Port		80			The Port is separated from the Host by a colon (:). If no port is specified, http schemes default to port 80 and https default to port 443
Path		dashboard.php		This points to the resource being accessed, which can be a file or a folder. If there is no path specified, the server returns the default index (e.g. index.html).
Query String	?login=true		the query string starts with a question mark (?), and consists of a parameter (e.g. login) and a value (e.g. true). Multiple parameters can be separated by an ampersand 					(&).
Fragments	#status			fragments are processed by the browsers on the client-side to locate sections within the primary resource (e.g. a header or section on the page).

--------------------------------------

HTTP Flow:

The first time a user enters the URL (inlanefrieght.com) into the browser it sends a request to a DNS (Domain Name Resolution) server to resolve the domain and get its IP address. The DNS server looks up the IP address for "inlanefreights.com" and returns it. All domain names need to be resolved this way as a server cant communicate without an IP address.

Our browsers usually first look up records in the local "/etc/hosts" file and if the requested domain does not exist within it they would contact other DNS servers. We can use the "/etc/hosts" to manually add records for DNS resolution by adding the IP address followed by the domain name.

Once the browser gets the IP address linked to the requested domain it sends a "get" request to the default HTTP port and asks for the root "/" path. then the web server receives the request and processes it. By default servers are configured to return an index file when a request for "/" is received.

Structure Example:

The user enters "inlanefreight.com" into a web browser, the web browser sends a "where is inlanefreight.com" to the DNS server, the DNS server sends the IP address "152.153.81.14" back to the web browser, the web browser sends an HTTP request to "152.153.81.14:80" and asks that IP to "Get/HTTP/1.1", then the InlaneFreight web server sends the "HTTP/1.1 200 OK" response back to the browser which gives the index.html and other folder contents for the website. The "200 OK" means that the request was successfully processed. 

