Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS):

*All communications are transferred in an encrypted format so even if third party does intercept the request they would not be able to extract the data out of it. Although the data transferred through the HTTPS protocol may be encrypted the request may still reveal the visited website URL if it contacted a clear text DNS server. For this reason it is recommended to utilize encrypted DNS servers or utilize a VPN service to ensure all traffic is properly encrypted. 


-----------------------------


HTTPS Flow:

1. The user types in "inlinefreight.com" into their browser.

2. the browser sends an HTTP request to inlanfreight.com:80 (GET\HTTP/1.1).

3. Then it gets moved permanently to HTTPS (HTTP/1.1 301 Moved Permanently).

4. Then the user gets connected to inlanfreight:443 (client Hello).

5. Then there's a server key exchange (server hello).

6. Then there's an encrypted handshake (client key exchange).

7. Then the encrypted handshake is finished (Finished).

8. Not the communication between the user and InlaneFreight is encrypted (Encrypted HTTP Communication).

---------------------------------


cURL for HTTPS:

*cURL should automatically handle all HTTPS communication standards and perform a secure handshake and then encrypt and decrypt data automatically. However, if we ever contact a website with an invalid SSL certificate or an outdated one the cURL by default would not proceed with the communication to protect against a man in the middle attack (MITM). We may face such an issue when testing a local web application or with a web application hosted for practice purposes, as such web applications may not yet have implemented a valid SSL certificate. To skip the certificate check with cURL we can use the "-k" flag. Example:

Romeltier1@htb[/htb]$ curl -k https://inlanefreight.com

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<html><head>
...SNIP...

